Why am I analysing the relationship between Scottish Battlefields and Roman roads?

Due to the availability of the existing Roman network, few roads were built by medieval kings of Britain (Bishop, 2014). However, they played an important strategic and tactical role in warfare.

Bishop (2014) notes that early medieval armies used Roman roads to move around, stating that there is an undeniable broad correlation between battle sites in Britain - especially in Britain- and the Roman road network.

Questions

Is the statement by Bishop true for Battlefields in Scotland?

Does this remain true in later periods?

Datasets

The battlefields dataset comes from the [Historic Environment Scotland (http://portal.historicenvironment.scot/spatialdownloads/battlefields)], and contains the location of nationally important battlfields in Scotland.

The Roman roads datasets comes from [The Digital Atlas of Roman and Medieval Civilisations (https://darmc.harvard.edu/data-availability)], and is a digitised version of the Roman roads identified in the Barington Atlas.

As the datasets are spatial, we need to make sure the data are in the same coordinate systems. This is important for plotting, as well as any analysis such as calculating distances between datasets.

crs(scot_battles)
## CRS arguments:
##  +proj=tmerc +lat_0=49 +lon_0=-2 +k=0.9996012717 +x_0=400000
## +y_0=-100000 +datum=OSGB36 +units=m +no_defs +ellps=airy
## +towgs84=446.448,-125.157,542.060,0.1502,0.2470,0.8421,-20.4894
crs(roman_roads)
## CRS arguments:
##  +proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs +ellps=WGS84 +towgs84=0,0,0
# Aany spatial analysis should be conducted from a planimetric coordinate system (e.g., osgb), rather than geographical (e.g., wgs84) 

roman_roads_osgb <- spTransform(roman_roads, crs(scot_battles))

identical(crs(scot_battles), crs(roman_roads_osgb))
## [1] TRUE

Lets quickly see how this looks

plot(scot_battles)
lines(roman_roads_osgb, col = "red")

To make the distance analysis easier, lets calculate the centroid point of each battlefield site.

scot_battles_centroid <- gCentroid(scot_battles, byid = TRUE)
plot(scot_battles)
points(scot_battles_centroid, col = "red", pch = 16, cex = 1)

Right now, the battlefield centroids lack any data. Lets add when the battle occured.

bf_dates <- NULL

# loops through the URLs in the scot_battles dataset. extracts the corresponding HTML for battledates and substrings to pull out the date. Writes to bf_dates.

for (i in 1:length(scot_battles$LINK)) {
  bf_date_string <- rvest::html_nodes(read_html(paste0(scot_battles$LINK[i], collapse = "")), ".battledate")
  bf_date_stringcut <-  unlist(str_extract_all(bf_date_string,"[[:digit:]]{4}"))
  bf_dates[i] <- as.vector(bf_date_stringcut)
  Sys.sleep(2)
}

bf_dates <- as.numeric(bf_dates)

# adds data to scot_battles_centroid to make it a SpatialPointsDataFrame class. 

scot_battles_centroid <- SpatialPointsDataFrame(scot_battles_centroid, as.data.frame(bf_dates))

Spatial visualisation

bf_pts <- as.data.frame(scot_battles_centroid)

roman_roads_df <- fortify(roman_roads_osgb)

uk_outline <- getData("GADM", country="GBR", level=1)

scotland_outline <- uk_outline[uk_outline$NAME_1 == "Scotland",]

scotland_outline_osgb <- spTransform(scotland_outline, crs(scot_battles_centroid))

scotland_outline_osgb_df <- fortify(scotland_outline_osgb, region="NAME_1")
map_plot <- ggplot(data = bf_pts, (aes(x, y))) +
  geom_polygon(data = scotland_outline_osgb_df, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group), fill = "gainsboro") + 
  geom_point(data = roman_roads_df[roman_roads_df$lat > 600000,], aes(x = long, y = lat ), colour = "#de2d26", size = 0.6) +
  geom_point() + 
  facet_wrap(~century, nrow = 1) + 
    theme_void()

map_plot

Distance Analysis

coords <- cbind(roman_roads_df$long, roman_roads_df$lat)
roman_roads_pts <-  SpatialPoints(coords)

crs(roman_roads_pts) <- proj4string(scot_battles_centroid)
distance <- data.frame()

for (i in levels(scot_battles_centroid$century)) { 
  battle_road_dist <- rgeos::gDistance(scot_battles_centroid[scot_battles_centroid$century == i,], roman_roads_pts, byid = TRUE)
  battle_road_dist_vect <- data.frame(as.vector(battle_road_dist))
  battle_road_dist_vect$century <- i
  distance <- rbind(distance, battle_road_dist_vect)
}

names(distance) <- c("Distance", "Century")
box_dist <- ggplot(distance, aes(Century, Distance)) + 
  geom_boxplot(colour = "gainsboro", fill = "gainsboro", width = 0.2) +  stat_summary(geom = "crossbar", width=0.2, fatten=2, colour="white", fun.data = function(x){ return(c(y=median(x), ymin=median(x), ymax=median(x))) })  + 
  theme_classic() +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  stat_summary(fun.y= median, geom="line", aes(group=1), colour = "#de2d26", size = 1) + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 16, colour = "#de2d26"))

box_dist + labs(y = "Distance from Roman roads nodes\nto battlefield centroids (m)")

Buffer Analysis

buffer <- data.frame()

for (i in c(1000, 2500, 5000, 10000, 25000)) { 
  road_buff <- rgeos::gBuffer(roman_roads_osgb, byid = TRUE, width = i, capStyle = "ROUND", joinStyle = "ROUND")
  over <- sp::over(scot_battles_centroid, road_buff)  
  over_pts <- scot_battles_centroid[!is.na(over$OBJECTID),]
  over_pts_proportion <- data.frame((tapply(over_pts$century, over_pts$century,length)) / (tapply(scot_battles_centroid$century, scot_battles_centroid$century, length)))
  over_pts_proportion$buffer <- i
  over_pts_proportion$decade <- rownames(over_pts_proportion)
  buffer <- rbind(buffer, over_pts_proportion)
}
  
str(buffer)
## 'data.frame':    30 obs. of  3 variables:
##  $ X.tapply.over_pts.century..over_pts.century..length....tapply.scot_battles_centroid.century..: Named num  NA 0.2 NA NA 0.0588 ...
##   ..- attr(*, "names")= chr  "1200s" "1300s" "1400s" "1500s" ...
##  $ buffer                                                                                       : num  1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 2500 2500 2500 2500 ...
##  $ decade                                                                                       : chr  "1200s" "1300s" "1400s" "1500s" ...
names(buffer) <- c("battlefield.proport", "Distance", "Century")

buffer$Distance <- as.factor(buffer$Distance)
buffer$Century <- as.factor(buffer$Century)

levels(buffer$Distance) <- c("1,000m from Roman roads", "2,500m from Roman roads", "5,000m from Roman roads", "10,000m from Roman roads", "25,000m from Roman roads")
distance_plot <- ggplot(buffer) + 
  geom_bar(aes(x = Century, y = battlefield.proport), fill = "gainsboro", stat = "identity") +
  facet_wrap(~Distance, nrow = 1) +
  labs(x = "Century", y = "Proportion of Battlefields within buffered\ndistance from Roman roads") + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) + 
  theme_classic() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

distance_plot

agg_dist <- aggregate(buffer$battlefield.proport, by = list(buffer$Distance), max, na.rm  = TRUE)

agg_dist$ismax <- "Max"

buffermax <- merge(buffer, agg_dist, by.x = c("battlefield.proport", "Distance"), by.y = c("x", "Group.1"), all.x = TRUE)

buffermax$ismax[is.na(buffermax$ismax)] <- "NotMax"

levels(buffermax$Distance) <- c("1,000m from Roman roads", "2,500m from Roman roads", "5,000m from Roman roads", "10,000m from Roman roads", "25,000m from Roman roads")
distance_max_plot <- ggplot(buffermax) + 
  geom_bar(aes(x = Century, y = battlefield.proport, fill = ismax), stat = "identity") + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c('#de2d26', "gainsboro")) +
  facet_wrap(~Distance, nrow = 1) +
  labs(x = "Century", y = "Proportion of Battlefields within buffered\ndistance from Roman roads") + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) + 
  theme_classic() + 
  guides(fill = FALSE) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

distance_max_plot

Final Visualisation

grid.arrange(map_plot + 
               labs(title =  "'Nearly all the battles on English soil have been fought either across [...] the old Roman roads, or in close proximity thereto' (Barrett, 1896)", subtitle = "True for Scotland? Does this remain true in later periods?") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 12)) + 
  theme(plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 16, colour = "#de2d26")),
  box_dist + 
      labs(x = "Century", y = "Distance from Roman roads\nto battlefield centroids (m)", title = "Distance from Roman roads to Scottish Battlefields increases over time") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 16, colour = "#de2d26")), 
  distance_max_plot + 
      labs(title = "Highest proportion of Battefields within buffered distance largely occur pre-1400s",x = "Century", y = "Proportion of Battlefields within buffered\ndistance from Roman roads", caption  ="Roman roads - darmc.harvard.edu/data-availability\nHistoric battles - portal.historicenvironment.scot/spatialdownloads/battlefields") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 16, colour = "#de2d26")), nrow = 3)
